USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the diligent effort with which Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of a sage, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he himself considered to be quite simple.
When he ended up letting his long-awaited doctrine sweat, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush’s Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of the Bush speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-torn Iraq as being “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the papers at present do not speak at all of Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but, objectively speaking, it left his successor with a much more favorable final situation than could be expected.
Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again in Afghanistan
It was again campaign commanders who called for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite the habits of subordination.
He asked 40,000 men to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least scammed the 10,000-strong general.
He managed to remove the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he was originally counting on 10,000.
What causes the most problems in the entire Obama strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete the whole process within three years.
Many doubt that a halving increase will bring the same fruits as progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan stands out as the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaties are respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only the dust in the eyes behind which will proliferate patriarchal ethnic relations.
It is unusually complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity about the relationships, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “quick-to-act state”, which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is perplexing because of his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-the-box heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "coming home soon" will bring about a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will view it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is turning negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the enhanced sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of a solution of the problem through the use of military force.
For example, it will have to be answered when, according to Obama, America comes to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will bring about a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only hurdle for Obama is the fact that he has three years left until the presidential election and therefore there is still enough time for him to plan for a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
