Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow down the proliferation of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, takes precedence over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on common variants of the virus as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS right now.
However, it is possible to radically prolong the lives of patients through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption causes a number of side effects.
In addition, the suppression of this multiplication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VICHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg, paves the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a way different from all drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings on virus proteins.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A traitorous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by HIV protease, there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, it will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers say in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic link, which is then systematically modified.
