We don’t want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations Group has draft plans for reducing emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- came back under fire on Friday, as a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bolstering most of the burden, in the next 40 years.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it illuminated the way forward.
But it has been seen as a major step forward in time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Written by a UN task force, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both on-going and long-term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what the upper limit of the global temperature rise would be that officials would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Sierra Club Representative in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary-General on climate change, Yvo de Boer, described as “the full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, from 25 to 45 percent compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, vowing to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
U.S. Climate Negotiation Representative Todd Stern rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison to voluntary efforts by major emerging economies, if these were not financed by developed countries.
This change is a sign that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions from major developing countries, Stern said, adding that the text did not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after China’s deputy foreign minister, He Yafei, said the U.S. chief negotiator either lacked “common sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing over their respective obligations as poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it was not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should suffer the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also a climate advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants say the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unit, said small island states’ action has “put political pressure on the entire political process,” in part because they are now unified and calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates have become an urgent matter, with delegates focusing on solving most of the pending problems before the heads of government reach an agreement.
Senior officials such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister got off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend in-house meetings and news conferences, in order to be able to make claims that will be considered over the next week.
The real picture of the rally -- where 13,000 people walk in and out of the Palais des Congrès every day -- guitar-playing activists presenting nightly shows mocking countries that they think betray themselves and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than via email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
Heavy trucks are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 225 km/h will redefine Monday’s syndrome
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transport revolution in Britain.
The country’s first high-speed commuter train will run from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes on the first Javelin commuter train outside London.
He hopes that the new service will allow Britain to integrate an international network of fast and reliable trains and will connect the major conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
Lost small holes will become thriving suburban towns, business travel times will be much shorter and moving from plane and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic jams on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhere to this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new railroad, the inevitable scheduling battle, and fears of environmental hazards are likely to curb British high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will return its document to Lord Adonis on December 30.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next planned step for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five meters of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment could be controversial.
In the countryside, the map will be drawn up to 25 meters from the final route.
It is also expected that HS2 will present three options for a larger high-speed network, going north.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in a Y configuration for which a high-speed line will go all the way to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two to or near Birmingham, with one branch going west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
“It looks like it will be the best performance option,” said one rail professional.
When this is over, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a one-hour journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making it the fastest British network in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow trains 400m long and can carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on one route London - Birmingham.
A terminal capable of accommodating 20,000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Given the space constraints, it is expected that an existing station will be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Experts in the rail industry say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should be put in place, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be made before a general election.
Even if he launches the machine, the network will have to be built part by part.
The trains will first be forced to run off high-speed lines on existing rails north of Birmingham, retaining travel times between London and Scotland of more than three hours.
This solution seems to be the best to ensure a passage from planes to trains, constituting a reference point for the rail revolution.
