The Management Revolution or the End of Economic Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been unsuccessful.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it was once, to impose on consumers products thought by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the business, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences returns regularly!
A demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "demands from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that the revenues of authoritarian management totally contradict.
That’s why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the center of the company’s concerns in the same way as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- Firstly because I have been able to see that, faced with a new situation, any structure finally manages, after many detours, to do first... what it has always done.!
Second, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of one’s own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US “neurosciences” and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by study institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the “levers” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a mechanistic governance posture, unsuitable for today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to achieve some of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from Motivational Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management back “in place.”
In this way, they create a favourable terrain for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: ‘Just War’ Brings Right Praise to Obama
The U.S. right on Friday welcomed Barack Obama’s speech in Oslo yesterday, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of “just war” against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had broached the award on Oct. 9, applauded the presidential speech, like Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, said Mrs. Palin, an aegis of the right wing of the Republican party, to the USA Today daily, adding that she herself addressed the "sometimes necessary" theme of war in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is of course the last thing in my opinion that Americans want to have to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped there, she said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done “a very good job” in Oslo.
I found the speech to be really good, said the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential speech.
On some sides, I found this speech entirely historic, Mr. Gingrich said, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former president, considered by some to be a possible Republican nominee for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind Nobel Committee members "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
For Michael Gerson, former George W. Bush pen converted columnist in the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech."
