The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hahae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50 meters high, its posterior limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been exceptional.
But, as reported by Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hahae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the supercontinent's landmass, the Pangaea, and was toward the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of Tawa lights up the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship ties, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team tells that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms some theories regarding the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the earliest dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians divided into three major evolutionary groups: theropods (carnivores) which include the later appeared tyrannosaurus and velociraptor and from which descend birds, sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and those related to them and ornithischian herbivores such as ornithischian species.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa was one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting ratio of features that are both primitive and developed, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found evidence to suggest that the Tawa hahae possessed small air bags in its skull-level bones, as do the birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hahae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed air bags and a light skeleton, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that Saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. the entire landmass that formed the supercontinent Pangaea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to him.
All three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the Natural History Museum of New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the sileosaur, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
How dinosaurs became the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, however, remains a mystery to this day.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other Saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread across the planet thus promoting the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction to which the dinosaurs randomly survived while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favorsthe flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and since that time has been in the shadows: it was mammals.
