The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be high enough.
For its supporters it is nothing less than the “new heart of Europe”.
If you will. S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into a desperate chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
Head-of-the-line stations, with lanes that ended in the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of 19th century transport technology that acted as the brake pad of modern rail traffic because it once took a long time to pass the locomotives from the back to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that’s what you have to do.
That is why head-of-line stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And also in Stuttgart: a train station, which is located about halfway on the Trans-European Magistral Railway between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realisation of the S21 project is really going to start, although the visions of the 80s have not been compatible with reality for a long time.
