The Worlds of Dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality merge.
As long as these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our darkened rooms, we can indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies without hindrance.
However, one who, awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at issue: it is the same neuronal activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but which sometimes pushes the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, at best it is called visions, at worst madness.
But even though the trigger and effect stand out, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, neurotransmitting substances of the brain - first of all dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine - breaks down and the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts often occur during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earth's force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreams.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awakening; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
