Unlike schizophrenia, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That’s why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
Unfortunately, in our overly conscious world, we quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called onyroid form of experience, a particular form of the modification of consciousness awakened by dreaming.
The dream experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is in a state of awakening.
The onyroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious and experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dreaming and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, a capacity of organization that is given to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book "Change of heart" as an action to safeguard the soul.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious goes on a journey several days after a heart valve operation followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain motionless in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from all quarters, visiting foreign places, traveling through time. He sees himself as an old man lying in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who make blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcycle who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He absorbs himself completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally distinguished from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and intensive than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, dreamlike delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "may cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite enriching.
