75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed in the study "Fructivity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their careers limited because of motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether or not the woman works, and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have a poorly stable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are reluctant to enter the couple's life and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those who work in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the start date of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the age gap between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those who attended elementary and higher education were first mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary school get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Ms. Delgado.
