After days since last spring, when asset inflation was the dominant rating in the markets, uncertainty resurfaces, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future of an uncertain nature.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at near-zero rates, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been practically finalized and, without questioning their non-conforming liquidity policy, are starting to put some sand in the wheels, as the ECB did, with their one-year auction next week.
